Rwanda and Namibia on Saturday became the latest African countries to confirm cases of the dreaded coronavirus. The new cases push the number of countries that have confirmed COVID-19 in the continent to at least 20. Rwanda's Health ministry said in a statement that the patient is an Indian citizen who arrived from Mumbai in India on March 8. “The patient had no symptoms upon arrival in Rwanda and reported himself to a health facility on March 13 where he was immediately tested,” the statement reads. The ministry said the patient is currently under treatment in stable condition, in isolation, as the government tracks down anyone he might have come in contact with. It urged the residents of Rwanda to continue observing all instructions from health authorities particularly washing of hands regularly, avoiding large gatherings and reporting any symptoms by calling toll free number 114. The Namibian Health ministry confirmed two cases on Saturday morning. With the new cases, at least 173 people across Africa have tested positive for the virus that has been declared a pandemic by the World Health Organization. Other countries that have confirmed the virus are Kenya, Sudan, Ethiopia, Guinea, Egypt, Morocco, Tunisia, Algeria, Senegal, Togo, Cameroon and Burkina Faso Others are the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), South Africa, Nigeria, Ivory Coast, Gabon and Ghana. Globally, the virus has infected at least 132,000 people and killed more than 5,000 others in at least 122 countries across the globe. Edited by R.Wamochie